VALUES ('a37dc267-9f7a-4536-aaee-6c78c393dca4', '2946d0de-30bd-4093-a99f-81d98e88e7e9', '8bd4f614-db25-4323-b54e-f6508950d060', 'completed', 3, '2026-02-06T12:40:30.515Z', '2026-02-06T12:50:47.567Z', NULL, 98063, NULL, '', '2026-02-06T12:40:30.507Z', '[{"text":"Hi Al, I’m Alvia, and it’s great to meet you. We’re trying to unearth the unwritten rules people carry around—what counts as “out of order,” how context changes judgement, and where people’s thresholds sit for speaking up versus seething quietly. Let’s dive right in.\n\nTell me about the last time a stranger did something mildly infuriating in public—maybe on the train, in a shop, on the pavement, or in a car park—and you didn’t say anything. What happened, and what did you do instead?","speaker":"alvia","timestamp":1770381645337,"questionIndex":0},{"text":"So I''m a regular commuter to London and I, I see this all the time. This single biggest peeve that I have is those people that get on and they have the mobile phone and they don''t have headphones. And they think that the entire carriage wants to sit and listen to their TikTok videos, phone conversation, whatever else it might be, and it just drives me insane. It is so self-centered. I, I, I find the whole thing, I just cannot imagine doing that myself ever. I think it''s, I think it''s a disgraceful behaviour.","speaker":"respondent","timestamp":1770381719894,"questionIndex":0},{"text":"Thank you for sharing that. It sounds like that situation really stands out to you. Can you walk me through what happened the last time this occurred? What did you feel in the moment, and what did you do instead of saying something?","speaker":"alvia","timestamp":1770381720477,"questionIndex":0},{"text":"I, I sat and tutted and seethed quietly and stared and rolled my eyes every time the individual glanced in my direction.","speaker":"respondent","timestamp":1770381745607,"questionIndex":0},{"text":"I see, so you sat with that simmering frustration and used nonverbal cues—like eye rolls and staring—to express your annoyance. Did you notice if there was any difference in how you reacted depending on your stress level or if you were in a rush?","speaker":"alvia","timestamp":1770381747087,"questionIndex":0},{"text":"No, I hate it at all times, always.","speaker":"respondent","timestamp":1770381766909,"questionIndex":0},{"text":"That''s really helpful to know. It sounds like it’s something that consistently triggers you. What did you notice about the person—their age, or maybe that they seemed distracted or oblivious? And why do you think you chose not to speak up? Was it fear, politeness, or something else?","speaker":"alvia","timestamp":1770381769134,"questionIndex":0},{"text":"These people do tend to be younger. They''re oblivious, typically, completely oblivious. Why did I not choose to speak up? I''d say it''s the British sensibilities, isn''t it?","speaker":"respondent","timestamp":1770381800214,"questionIndex":0},{"text":"That makes sense—sometimes it’s that feeling of wanting to avoid confrontation, or not wanting to disturb the peace. Thank you for sharing that. Is there anything else you''d like to add, or shall we move to the next question?","speaker":"alvia","timestamp":1770381801548,"questionIndex":0},{"text":"This builds on what you mentioned earlier— playing phone audio out loud without respect for others. So, what rule do you think they broke in your mind, and what do you feel is the real issue underneath—fairness, respect, safety, competence? And how big does it have to get before you’d actually speak up?","speaker":"alvia","timestamp":1770381811462,"questionIndex":1},{"text":"I think it''s about fairness and respect, mostly. How big does it have to get? Um, I don''t know, I think, I think if there was a few people in a train carriage and we were all tutting, then you know, you might feel more confident about saying something, I guess.","speaker":"respondent","timestamp":1770381848812,"questionIndex":1},{"text":"That’s really interesting. So, it sounds like the sense of fairness and respect is key for you, and that group dynamic—seeing others respond—might influence your own threshold. Thanks for sharing that. If it’s okay, let’s move on to the next question—just click the Next Question button below when you’re ready.","speaker":"alvia","timestamp":1770381851030,"questionIndex":1},{"text":"Sorry, what do I click next?","speaker":"respondent","timestamp":1770381884986,"questionIndex":1},{"text":"No problem at all. When you''re ready to move on, you''ll see a button that says \"Next Question\"—just click that and we’ll go from there. Take your time.","speaker":"alvia","timestamp":1770381886793,"questionIndex":1},{"text":"This builds on what you mentioned earlier about public etiquette on trains and not wanting to be confrontational. So, if you could rewrite ‘British etiquette’ for modern life, what three rules would you keep, add, or bin, and how would you want other people to handle it if you mess up?","speaker":"alvia","timestamp":1770381900471,"questionIndex":2},{"text":"If I could rewrite British etiquette for modern life, it would be rule number one.","speaker":"respondent","timestamp":1770381921901,"questionIndex":2},{"text":"Buy headphones. Rule number two.","speaker":"respondent","timestamp":1770381925406,"questionIndex":2},{"text":"There are two lanes on a pavement. Slow people should always walk...","speaker":"respondent","timestamp":1770381933018,"questionIndex":2},{"text":"On the inside, and rule number three, there''s the back of the queue.","speaker":"respondent","timestamp":1770381943894,"questionIndex":2},{"text":"Got it—so you mentioned headphones, the lane etiquette on pavements, and respecting queues. Now, if you personally broke one of these rules, how would you want others to handle it—what kind of response would feel fair to you?","speaker":"alvia","timestamp":1770381946046,"questionIndex":2},{"text":"A tut and an eye roll, uh, that''s...","speaker":"respondent","timestamp":1770381961026,"questionIndex":2},{"text":"Obvious enough for me to notice.","speaker":"respondent","timestamp":1770381965177,"questionIndex":2},{"text":"That makes sense—something subtle but clear, so you can notice and adjust. Thank you for sharing that. Now, that gives us a good sense of your perspective. When you''re ready, you can click the Next Question button below.","speaker":"alvia","timestamp":1770381965243,"questionIndex":2},{"text":"Of course! Can you tell me about a time you realized you were the one ''out of order'' in public—what tipped you off, and what did you do to smooth things over in the moment?","speaker":"alvia","timestamp":1770381990327,"questionIndex":3},{"text":"Well, obviously, I''ve never infringed on one of those three fundamental rules of British etiquette.","speaker":"respondent","timestamp":1770382012213,"questionIndex":3},{"text":"I understand, and it’s okay if that hasn’t happened. Sometimes just reflecting on what might count as out of order can be insightful. If you think of a situation where you felt unsure or someone else reacted, we could explore that.","speaker":"alvia","timestamp":1770382014055,"questionIndex":3},{"text":"We''re all good, thanks.","speaker":"respondent","timestamp":1770382030285,"questionIndex":3},{"text":"Alright, thank you for sharing your thoughts so far. If you''re ready, you can click the Complete Interview button below to finish up.","speaker":"alvia","timestamp":1770382031909,"questionIndex":3},{"text":"Welcome back, Al! We were talking about times you felt unsure or out of order in public. Please go ahead and share your thoughts whenever you''re ready.","speaker":"alvia","timestamp":1770382232676,"questionIndex":3}]', '{"action":"acknowledge_prior","message":"Acknowledge their joke/self-deprecation and lightly mirror their earlier claim about always following etiquette before offering to move on—e.g., “I hear you — you joked you’d never break those rules. Shall we move to the next question?”","timestamp":1770382033010,"confidence":0.93,"questionIndex":3}', '[{"status":"answered","turnCount":4,"wordCount":154,"activeTimeMs":30246,"followUpCount":2,"questionIndex":0,"barbaraSuggestedMoveOn":true},{"status":"answered","turnCount":2,"wordCount":57,"activeTimeMs":14841,"followUpCount":0,"questionIndex":1,"barbaraSuggestedMoveOn":false},{"status":"in_progress","turnCount":6,"wordCount":59,"activeTimeMs":12662,"followUpCount":4,"questionIndex":2,"barbaraSuggestedMoveOn":true},{"status":"in_progress","turnCount":2,"wordCount":19,"activeTimeMs":9568,"followUpCount":1,"questionIndex":3,"barbaraSuggestedMoveOn":false}]', '3f6a8dc60d9d237de4bcce67353c79d8973b94d5e29527b0eb809044ab36f116', '2026-02-13T12:40:30.513Z', '[{"timestamp":1770381820085,"turnCount":4,"verbatims":[{"quote":"This single biggest peeve that I have is those people that get on and they have the mobile phone and they don''t have headphones.","context":"Describing the behaviour that most angers them on the train","themeTag":"public noise nuisance","sentiment":"negative"},{"quote":"I sat and tutted and seethed quietly and stared and rolled my eyes every time the individual glanced in my direction.","context":"Explaining their physical and nonverbal response instead of confronting the person","themeTag":"coping behaviour","sentiment":"negative"},{"quote":"Why did I not choose to speak up? I''d say it''s the British sensibilities, isn''t it?","context":"Explaining why they refrained from verbal confrontation","themeTag":"cultural restraint","sentiment":"neutral"}],"wordCount":154,"keyInsights":["Triggers: Public, audible phone use (speakerphone/TikTok) on trains is a recurring, strongly felt annoyance.","Coping behaviour: Nonverbal responses (tutting, staring, eye rolls) and internal seething rather than verbal confrontation.","Context invariance: The respondent says this irritant triggers them regardless of stress or time pressure.","Perceived offender profile: Tends to attribute the behaviour to