VALUES ('b1351c8c-5ff1-48d4-b465-0905ef1a6b4d', '2946d0de-30bd-4093-a99f-81d98e88e7e9', '8bd4f614-db25-4323-b54e-f6508950d060', 'completed', 3, '2026-02-06T12:53:16.930Z', '2026-02-06T13:00:58.559Z', NULL, 513035, NULL, '', '2026-02-06T12:53:16.923Z', '[{"text":"Hi Pat, I''m Alvia. It’s great to have you here. We’re trying to unearth the unwritten rules people carry around—what counts as “out of order,” how context changes judgment, and where people’s personal thresholds sit for speaking up versus stewing quietly. The first question: Tell me about the last time a stranger did something mildly infuriating in public—maybe on a train, in a shop, or somewhere else—and you didn’t say anything. What happened, and what did you do instead?","speaker":"alvia","timestamp":1770382411205,"questionIndex":0},{"text":"I was walking out of the train station the other evening.","speaker":"respondent","timestamp":1770382435966,"questionIndex":0},{"text":"Thanks for sharing that. It sounds like it was pretty frustrating. Can you tell me more about how you felt physically in that moment—what did you notice in your body?","speaker":"alvia","timestamp":1770382476358,"questionIndex":0},{"text":"I walked through the gate and there was a guy, a young lad. He was on a phone. He was playing a game and he was walking along quite a narrow passageway, taking up the entire passageway, walking right in the middle of it and walking at about two miles an hour and holding up the entire train behind him. And every time I went to step past him on the right, he just shuffled slightly right. Then I went left and of course he shuffled slightly left. And in the end, I managed to get past him and tutted very loudly on the way through.","speaker":"respondent","timestamp":1770382477077,"questionIndex":0},{"text":"Oh, I just, yeah, I got really, really, really aggravated and really tense, and I think I might have called him something on the way past, to be honest with you.","speaker":"respondent","timestamp":1770382507820,"questionIndex":0},{"text":"Thanks for sharing that. It sounds like you were holding a lot of tension. What did that aggravation feel like—was it mainly frustration, or something else?","speaker":"alvia","timestamp":1770382508719,"questionIndex":0},{"text":"Mainly frustration, yeah.","speaker":"respondent","timestamp":1770382521176,"questionIndex":0},{"text":"Got it, thank you for explaining that. So you felt mostly frustration building up in that moment. Is there anything else you''d like to add, or shall we move to the next question?","speaker":"alvia","timestamp":1770382522695,"questionIndex":0},{"text":"This builds on what you mentioned earlier—so what rule do you feel they broke in your mind? And what''s the real issue underneath it—fairness, respect, safety, competence? And how big does it have to be before you''d actually speak up?","speaker":"alvia","timestamp":1770382532849,"questionIndex":1},{"text":"It''s about...","speaker":"respondent","timestamp":1770382546278,"questionIndex":1},{"text":"Competence, I think, mainly in this particular instance. How incompetent do you have to be to not appreciate that there are others around you?","speaker":"respondent","timestamp":1770382557505,"questionIndex":1},{"text":"So there''s definitely a self-centeredness element which extends, I guess, into respect.","speaker":"respondent","timestamp":1770382564474,"questionIndex":1},{"text":"But it drives me mad.","speaker":"respondent","timestamp":1770382567752,"questionIndex":1},{"text":"I completely understand. That sense of self-centeredness and lack of awareness can really push your buttons. Can you say whether the issue feels mainly incompetence or entitlement? And at what point—like if they had kids, or if they looked stressed—would you cut them some slack versus speaking up?","speaker":"alvia","timestamp":1770382570472,"questionIndex":1},{"text":"It''s a good question. Entitlement, yes, definitely. Of course, if they had kids or if they were worried or whatever, there was none of that with this guy. He was just in a world of his own, drifting merrily along.","speaker":"respondent","timestamp":1770382597397,"questionIndex":1},{"text":"Thanks for that. So it sounds like if someone had a valid reason—like being stressed or distracted—you might be more understanding. What’s the tipping point for you, when you feel you’d really need to speak up?","speaker":"alvia","timestamp":1770382599229,"questionIndex":1},{"text":" tipping point is when they''re visibly, you know, not distracted by kids or anything like that, and it''s just about their self-absorption, I guess.","speaker":"respondent","timestamp":1770382625570,"questionIndex":1},{"text":"Thank you for sharing that. It sounds like the key issue for you is when it feels like pure self-absorption, with no external reason. Is there anything else you''d like to add, or shall we move to the next question?","speaker":"alvia","timestamp":1770382627284,"questionIndex":1},{"text":"This builds on what you mentioned earlier about awareness of others and respect for shared space. So, if you could rewrite British etiquette for modern life, what three rules would you keep, add, or bin? And how would you want other people to handle it if you mess up?","speaker":"alvia","timestamp":1770382641433,"questionIndex":2},{"text":"So if I could rewrite, well, I don''t know what the British etiquette for modern life is, can you tell me?","speaker":"respondent","timestamp":1770382659075,"questionIndex":2},{"text":"Sure, I can offer a bit of context. In modern life, British etiquette often focuses on things like being considerate in public spaces, respecting personal boundaries, and showing patience. Now, thinking along those lines, what three rules would you keep, add, or remove? And how would you want others to approach it if you slip up?","speaker":"alvia","timestamp":1770382661643,"questionIndex":2},{"text":"Number one, pick up your litter. Number two...","speaker":"respondent","timestamp":1770382685308,"questionIndex":2},{"text":"Yeah, respecting personal boundaries. Yeah, there''s nothing worse than somebody walking too close to you when there''s the space around. I''ve got no problem on the tube, I understand it then. Um, but, but when there''s plenty of space around, but then someone just gets a bit too close, that, that drives me mad.","speaker":"respondent","timestamp":1770382702909,"questionIndex":2},{"text":"Number three, merge in turn would be number three on my list.","speaker":"respondent","timestamp":1770382711334,"questionIndex":2},{"text":"Great, that gives us a solid set: picking up litter, respecting personal boundaries, and merging in turn. Now, if you mess up, how would you want others to handle it? A nod, a quiet word, something else?","speaker":"alvia","timestamp":1770382713515,"questionIndex":2},{"text":"A quiet word, I think, is a very British way of doing it.","speaker":"respondent","timestamp":1770382727378,"questionIndex":2},{"text":"That makes sense—a quiet word can keep things calm and respectful. Just to follow up, have you ever found yourself breaking any of those rules yourself? For example, do you ever get caught up and miss something?","speaker":"alvia","timestamp":1770382729527,"questionIndex":2},{"text":"I''m sure I do, but I do, when I''m out and about, I do try and remain conscious of what''s going on around me and, and, you know, the role that I have to play as a good British citizen.","speaker":"respondent","timestamp":1770382754947,"questionIndex":2},{"text":"That’s really thoughtful of you, and it sounds like you try to stay aware and considerate. Thank you for sharing that. Now, let’s move on—feel free to click the Next Question button below when you''re ready.","speaker":"alvia","timestamp":1770382757106,"questionIndex":2},{"text":"Absolutely. So, thinking about the other side of your threshold—can you tell me about a recent moment when you did decide to say something? What exactly did you say, how did they react, and how did it feel afterwards?","speaker":"alvia","timestamp":1770382781815,"questionIndex":3},{"text":"So I have spoken to people about having their phones on.","speaker":"respondent","timestamp":1770382795897,"questionIndex":3},{"text":"On the train.","speaker":"respondent","timestamp":1770382797348,"questionIndex":3},{"text":"Without headphones.","speaker":"respondent","timestamp":1770382799276,"questionIndex":3},{"text":"That''s a real pet peeve of mine, and I did mention that to somebody once. Actually, it snapped them out of it, and they said, oh, sorry, and quickly turned the volume down. But yeah, the lack of self-awareness again never fails to amaze me.","speaker":"respondent","timestamp":1770382819128,"questionIndex":3},{"text":"Thank you for sharing that. It sounds like it worked out okay in that situation. Can you tell me more about how you felt right after you spoke up and how you felt later on?","speaker":"alvia","timestamp":1770382820735,"questionIndex":3},{"text":"I felt tense and nervous at the time, and when they said sorry, I felt quite relieved and pleased with myself for having made a point.","speaker":"respondent","timestamp":1770382839815,"questionIndex":3},{"text":"Thank you for sharing that. It''s really helpful to hear how that relief and sense of accomplishment came through. Is there anything else you''d like to add, or shall we move on?","speaker":"alvia","timestamp":1770382841933,"questionIndex":3}]', '{"action":"acknowledge_prior","message":"Acknowledge that they already described a similar ‘lack of self-awareness’ theme earlier (blocking passage, entitlement) before following up—then ask if that incident felt similar in how it triggered you and whether your threshold to speak was the same.","timestamp":1770382843244,"confidence":0.86,"questionIndex":3}', '[{"status":"answered","turnCount":4,"wordCount":151,"activeTimeMs":48673,"followUpCount":0,"questionIndex":0,"barbaraSuggestedMoveOn":true},{"status":"answered","turnCount":6,"wo